          "body": "The chapter's opening oracle (21:2-7) is designed to destroy one specific theological misreading: that the coming Babylonian invasion is merely a geopolitical event. The LORD commands Ezekiel to set his face toward Jerusalem and the sanctuaries — not toward Babylon — because the sword originates with God, not with Nebuchadnezzar. 'I will draw My sword out of its sheath' (21:3) is the chapter's foundational claim. The sword belongs to the LORD before it belongs to any army. This is covenant theology — specifically the sword-curse of Leviticus 26:25 ('I will bring a sword upon you') — made historically specific in the Babylonian campaign. The most disturbing element of the oracle is its indiscriminate reach: the sword cuts off 'the righteous and the wicked' (21:3-4), sweeping from south to north. This is not moral indifference; it is the nature of national covenantal judgment. When a covenant community falls, the innocent suffer with the guilty — a reality that drove Habakkuk's theodicy (Habakkuk 1:12-17) and Ezekiel's own wrestling earlier in the book (ch. 9, 18). The purpose stated in 21:5 — 'all flesh will know that I, the LORD, have drawn My sword' — reveals that the judgment serves universal doxology: God's sovereignty is displayed before nations that had watched Israel's syncretism and wondered if the LORD was a God of consequence."
