          "body": "The chapter's fourth and final oracle (21:28-32) turns to Ammon, who had apparently gloated over Judah's fall — the 'reproach' (*cherpah*) of 21:28 likely refers to Ammon's taunt at Judah's destruction (cf. Ezekiel 25:3, 6). Ammon had been spared at the fork in the road (21:20) — Nebuchadnezzar's divination pointed to Jerusalem first. But the sword that passed Ammon by is described in 21:28 with the same vocabulary as the sword against Israel: 'drawn, polished for the slaughter, to flash like lightning.' The instrument is identical; only the timing differs. Ammon's false prophets had offered 'false visions' and 'lying divinations' (21:29), presumably promising the nation's safety. The oracle dismantles that comfort: Ammon will be judged 'in the land of your origin' (21:30), will receive God's indignation and fire of wrath (21:31), and 'will not be remembered' (21:32). The closing silence of Ammon — not merely defeated but erased from memory — stands against Israel's preserved future (21:27). Israel endures through the triple ruin to the coming King; Ammon is consumed and forgotten. The chapter's last words are the divine authority formula: 'I, the LORD, have spoken.' Every oracle, every sword-word, every theophanic image, and every Messianic reservation rests on that ultimate ground."
